1.Introduction to Python

Python is a free, open-source programming language. Therefore, all you have to do is install Python once, and you can start working with it.

1.0 Why Python

Python works on different platforms (Windows, Mac, Linux, Raspberry Pi, etc)
Python has a simple syntax similar to the English language.
Python has syntax that allows developers to write programs with fewer lines than some other programming languages.
Python is also a cross-platform compatible language. So, what does this mean? Well, you can install and run Python on several operating systems. Whether you have a Windows, Mac, or Linux, you can rest assured that Python will work on all these operating systems.

Python is also a great visualization tool. It provides libraries such as Matplotlib, Seaborn, and bokeh to create stunning visualizations.

2. Comments

  • Comments can be used to explain Python code
  • Comments can be used to make the code more readable
  • Comments can be used to prevent execution when testing code

2.0 Creating a Comment

Comments starts with a #, and Python will ignore them:

2.1 Types of Comments

a - Single Line Comments

A single-line comment starts and ends in the same line. We use the # symbol to write a single-line comment. For example

In [37]:
# create a variable
name = 'John Deo'

# print the value
print(name)

John Deo

Note Here, we have created two single-line comments:

  • create a variable
  • print the value
  • Both starts with # sign

Here, code before # are executed and code after # are ignored by the interpreter.

b-Multi-line Comments

Python doesn't offer a separate way to write multiline comments. However, there are other ways to get around this issue.

We can use # at the beginning of each line of comment on multiple lines. For example,

In [ ]:
# This is a long comment
# and it extends
# to multiple lines

Here, each line is treated as a single comment, and all of them are ignored.

Another way of doing this is to use triple quotes, either ''' or """.

These triple quotes are generally used for multi-line strings. But if we do not assign it to any variable or function, we can use it as a comment.

The interpreter ignores the string that is not assigned to any variable or function.

Let's see an example,

In [9]:
''' This is a long comment
and it extends
to multiple lines  '''
Out[9]:
' This is a long comment\nand it extends\nto multiple lines  '

3. Variables in Python

Variables are containers for storing data values. Here is an example of a variable: x=100

In the below diagram, the box holds a value of 100 and is named as x. Therefore, the variable is x, and the data it holds is the value.

The data type for a variable is the type of data it holds.

In the above example, x is holding 100, which is a number, and the data type of x is a number. In python we can store integers, decimals or characters in these variables.

3.1 Variables creation

Python variables do not need explicit declaration to reserve memory space or you can say to create a variable. A Python variable is created automatically when you assign a value to it. The equal sign (=) is used to assign values to variables.

The operand to the left of the = operator is the name of the variable and the operand to the right of the = operator is the value stored in the variable. For example −

In [11]:
counter = 100          # Creates an integer variable
miles   = 1000.0       # Creates a floating point variable
name    = "John"       # Creates a string variable

3.2 Printing Python Variables

Once we create a Python variable and assign a value to it, we can print it using print() function. Following is the extension of previous example and shows how to print different variables in Python:

In [13]:
print (counter)
print (miles)
print (name)

100
1000.0
John

NOTE-Here, 100, 1000.0 and "John" are the values assigned to counter, miles, and name variables, respectively. The Python program, produces the above result

3.3 Rules for Naming Python Variables

  • A variable name must start with a letter or the underscore character
  • A variable name cannot start with a number
  • A variable name can only contain alpha-numeric characters and underscores (A-z, 0-9, and _ )
  • Variable names are case-sensitive (age, Age and AGE are three different variables)
  • A variable name cannot be any of the Python keywords.

Legal variable names:

  • myvar = "Johne"
  • my_var = "Johne"
  • _my_var = "Johne"
  • myVar = "Johne"
  • MYVAR = "Johne"
  • myvar2 = "Johne"

Illegal variable names:

  • myvar = "Johne"
  • my-var = "Johne"
  • my var = "Johne"

4.1.1 Numeric Data Type

In Python, numeric data type is used to hold numeric values.

Integers, floating-point numbers and complex numbers fall under Python numbers category. They are defined as int, float and complex classes in Python.

  • int - holds signed integers of non-limited length.

num1 = 5

  • float - holds floating decimal points and it's accurate up to 15 decimal places.

num2 = 2.0

  • complex - holds complex number

num3 = 1+2j

more info on complex numbers visit https://byjus.com/maths/complex-numbers/

Note we can check the type of the data type in python using type() function to know which class a variable or a value belongs to. Example is shown below

In [38]:
num1 = 5
num2 = 2.0
num3 = 1+2j

print(num1, 'is of type', type(num1))
print(num2, 'is of type', type(num2))
print(num3, 'is of type', type(num3))

5 is of type <class 'int'>
2.0 is of type <class 'float'>
(1+2j) is of type <class 'complex'>

Explanation of code execution

In the above example, we have created three variables named num1, num2 and num3 with values 5, 5.0, and 1+2j respectively.

We have also used the type() function to know which class a certain variable belongs to.

Since,

  • 5 is an integer value, type() returns int as the class of num1 i.e <class 'int'>
  • 2.0 is a floating value, type() returns float as the class of num2 i.e <class 'float'>
  • 1 + 2j is a complex number, type() returns complex as the class of num3 i.e <class 'complex'>

6.Slicing strings

Python slicing is about obtaining a sub-string from the given string by slicing it respectively from start to end.

Python slicing can be done in two ways:

  • 1.Using a slice() method
  • 2.Using the array slicing [:: ] method

Below are the possible examples that we will be covering for slice and array slicing ,the summary is shown below along with the respective outputs . The string taken is "Coding worlds "

Method 1: Understanding slice() method

Syntax:¶

slice( Start_Index, End_Index, Steps )

  • Here, Start_Index is the starting index of the string.
  • End_Index is the last index before which all elements are considered.
  • Steps are the number of steps to be jumped in each iteration. The Start_Index and Steps are optional.
  • The Start_Index is 0 by default. The step is 1 by default.

Let's look at a few examples to understand string slicing in python.

4.1.3 Tuples

A Python tuple is an immutable ordered sequence of items. In other words, existing objects in the sequence cannot be modified, and new elements cannot be added once the sequence is created. A tuple consists of several values separated by commas. Unlike a Python list, tuples are enclosed within parentheses “( )”. We are covering the below topics in Tuple.

  • 1.Features of Python Tuple
  • 2.Creating of Tuple:
  • 3.Accessing Tuple Elements
  • 4.Slicing
  • 5.Deleting a Tuple
  • 6.Iterating Through a Tuple
  • 7.Advantages of Tuple over List in Python
  • 8.Differences Between Lists and Tuples

1:Features of Python Tuple

  • Tuples are an immutable data type, which means that once they have been generated, their elements cannot be changed.
  • Since tuples are ordered sequences, each element has a specific order that will never change.

2:Creating Tuple

To create a tuple, all the objects (or "elements") must be enclosed in parenthesis (), each one separated by a comma. Although it is not necessary to include parentheses, doing so is advised.

A tuple can contain any number of items, including ones with different data types (dictionary, string, float, list, etc.) Below are the examples.

In [10]:
# Python program to show how to create a tuple    
# Example1 :Creating an empty tuple    
empty_tuple = ()    
print("Example1 :Creating the Empty tuple-> ", empty_tuple)    
    
# Example2 :Creating tuple having integers    
int_tuple = (4, 6, 8, 10, 12, 14)    
print("Example2 :Tuple with integers-> ", int_tuple)    
    
# Example3 :Creating a tuple having objects of different data types    
mixed_tuple = (4, "Python", 9.3)    
print("Example3 : Tuple with different data types-> ", mixed_tuple)    
    
#Example4 : Creating a nested tuple    
nested_tuple = ("Python", {4: 5, 6: 2, 8:2}, (5, 3, 5, 6))    
print("Example4 : A nested tuple-> ", nested_tuple)    

#Example 5 :Creating tuple without parentheses
my_tuple = 1, 2, 3
print("Example5 : A tuple without parentheses -> ", my_tuple)    

Example1 :Creating the Empty tuple->  ()
Example2 :Tuple with integers->  (4, 6, 8, 10, 12, 14)
Example3 : Tuple with different data types->  (4, 'Python', 9.3)
Example4 : A nested tuple->  ('Python', {4: 5, 6: 2, 8: 2}, (5, 3, 5, 6))
Example5 : A tuple without parentheses ->  (1, 2, 3)

In the above example, we have created different types of tuples and stored different data items inside them.

3:Access Python Tuple Elements

The process of accessing elements from a tuple, works similar to strings and lists.

You can access individual elements of a tuple using indexing and a range of elements using slicing. In Python tuples, index starts from 0 and keeps increasing by 1 with every element in the tuple. This is called Positive Indexing(or indexing from the beginning). If there are n elements in a tuple, the 1st element will have index of 0 and the last element will have index n-1.

Python also allows negative indexing of tuples(indexing from the end). If there are n elements in a list, the last element will have index of -1 and the first element will have index -n.

7.Advantages of Tuple over List in Python

  • 1:We generally use tuples for heterogeneous (different) data types and lists for homogeneous (similar) data types.
  • 2:Since tuples are immutable, iterating through a tuple is faster than with a list. So there is a slight performance boost.
  • 3:Tuples that contain immutable elements can be used as a key for a dictionary. With lists, this is not possible.
  • 4:If you have data that doesn't change, implementing it as tuple will guarantee that it remains write-protected.

8.Differences Between Lists and Tuples

  • 1:The major difference between lists and tuples is that tuples are immutable. So a tuple can’t be changed through another reference elsewhere in the program. However, lists can be altered at any stage of the program.

  • 2:Tuples can’t be copied. tuple(my_tuple) returns you the same tuple. Lists can be copied.

  • 3:Tuples occupy a smaller memory compared to lists as they are immutable. This makes tuples a bit faster.

  • 4:Tuples are of fixed lengths. So you can’t add or remove elements from a tuple.

1.Introduction

A Python dictionary is an ordered list of key-value pairs. The items in the dictionary are comma separated key-value pairs. Keys in Python dictionary are immutable and must be unique whereas values are mutable and can be modified or changed anytime.

Dictionary in Python is defined inside curly braces ‘{ }’. Each key is separated by a from its value by a colon (:) and to access and assign value, indexing operator ‘[ ]’ is used.

If we have the key, we can retrieve its value anytime, however vice-versa doesn’t work. Hence Python dictionaries are used and optimized for retrieving data when the key is known. In the below figure we have a dictionary name py_dict holding key and value

Understanding keys:

Keys are immutable ( which cannot be changed ) data types that can be either strings or numbers. However, a key can not be a mutable data type, for example, a list. Keys are unique within a Dictionary and can not be duplicated inside a Dictionary. If it is used more than once, subsequent entries will overwrite the previous value. Key connects with the value, hence, creating a map-like structure. For example, remove keys from the picture; all you are left with is a data structure containing a sequence of numbers Dictionaries, therefore, hold a key: value pair at each position.

2.get(key , default ) method

The get(key, default) method is a built-in method in Python dictionaries that allows you to retrieve the value associated with a specific key. If the key is not present in the dictionary, it returns a default value that you can specify. The method takes two arguments:

key: The key for which you want to retrieve the value from the dictionary. default: The value to be returned if the key is not present in the dictionary. This is an optional parameter, and if not provided, it defaults to None. Here's an example to illustrate the usage of the get(key, default) method:

In [ ]:
# Define a dictionary
fruits = {'apple': 3, 'banana': 5, 'cherry': 2}

# Retrieve value for a valid key
apple_count = fruits.get('apple', 0)
print("Number of apples:", apple_count)  # Output: Number of apples: 3

# Retrieve value for an invalid key
orange_count = fruits.get('orange', 0)
print("Number of oranges:", orange_count)  # Output: Number of oranges: 0

# Retrieve value for an invalid key with a default value specified
grape_count = fruits.get('grape', -1)
print("Number of grapes:", grape_count)  # Output: Number of grapes: -1
Code Explanation

In the above example, we have a dictionary fruits that stores the counts of various fruits. We use the get() method to retrieve the counts of apples, oranges, and grapes. Since 'apple' and 'banana' are valid keys in the fruits dictionary, we get their respective counts.

However, 'orange' and 'grape' are not valid keys in the fruits dictionary, so we get the default values of 0 and -1 respectively, which we specified as the second argument to the get() method.

4.1.6 Decision making

Decision making statements in python are an essential tool for any programmer. They allow any program to make intelligent and informed decisions by evaluating information before executing that particular code. Decision making statements can direct a program to execute on the based of instructions if a certain condition is True or another if it's False. Different decision making structures can be used such as if statements, else-if statements, and nested if else statements for decision making in python programming language. Each decision structure has its own benefits and applications; however, decision making statements provide an invaluable tool for programming complex conditions in Python.

Types of decision-making in python

There are three types of decision making statements in python language, those are

  1. If statements in python
  2. If else statement in python
  3. Nested if else statement in python
1. If statements

if statement is the most simple form of decision-making statement. It takes an expression and checks if the expression evaluates to True then the block of code in if statement will be executed.

If the expression evaluates to False, then the block of code is skipped.

  Statement 2

  Statement n

  print('num is greater than 10')
print('if block ended')

if block ended
Code Explanation

In example 1, we see that the condition a==b evaluates to True. Therefore, the block of code inside if statement is executed.

In example 2, the condition evaluates to False, therefore, the print statement was not executed and the only statement that got executed was because it was outside the if block.

Note: Don’t forget to add a colon(:) after if statement and indent the statements properly that are executed when a condition is True.

4.1.7 Loops

In a programming language, a loop is a statement that contains instructions that continually repeat until a certain condition is reached.

Loops help us remove the redundancy of code when a task has to be repeated several times. With the use of loops, we can cut short those hundred lines of code to a few. Suppose you want to print the text “Hello, World!” 10 times. Rather than writing a print statement 10 times, you can use loops by indicating the number of repetitions needed.

The three types of loops in Python programming are while loop, for loop, and nested loops.But before that lets understand range function

The range() function returns a sequence of numbers between the give range

Types of Loops
1.While Loop

Inside the while loop, the statement (code) can be a single statement or a block of statements. The condition may be anything per our requirement, and we can use if, elif, or else in the code. The loop stops running when the condition fails (become false), and the execution will move to the next line of code. Indentation (also called white space) is necessary while defining a statement or code to be executed. Indentation is used to specify program structure and to group statements together in blocks.

It first checks the condition, executes the conditional code if it is TRUE, and checks the condition again. Program control exits the loop if the condition is FALSE.

In [1]:
count = 0
while count < 5:
    print("Count:", count)
    count += 1

Count: 0
Count: 1
Count: 2
Count: 3
Count: 4
Code Explanation

The variable count is initialized with a value of 0.

The while loop begins, and it continues to execute as long as the condition count < 5 is true.

Within each iteration of the loop, the current value of count is printed along with the string "Count:" using the print() function.

After printing, the value of count is incremented by 1 using the count += 1 statement.

The loop repeats until the condition count < 5 becomes false, which means count reaches a value of 5.

Overall, this code will print the numbers 0, 1, 2, 3, and 4, each on a separate line, because the loop runs five times (once for each value of count from 0 to 4).

2.For Loop

A python for loop is used to iterate over data structures like python lists, arrays, dictionaries, sets, tuples or even strings.

Loop statements will be executed for each item of the sequence.

In [2]:
#Example
nums = [10, 20, 30, 40, 50]
for i in nums:
    print(i)

10
20
30
40
50
Code Explanation

The list nums is defined with five elements: 10, 20, 30, 40, and 50.

The for loop begins, and in the first iteration, the value of i is set to 10 (the first element of nums).

The value of i (which is 10) is printed.

The loop moves to the next iteration, and now i is set to 20 (the second element of nums).

The value of i (which is 20) is printed.

This process continues for each element in nums, printing each element one by one.

3. Nested Loop

Nested loops mean using a loop inside another loop. We can use any type of loop inside any type of loop. We can use a while loop inside for loop, a for loop inside a while loop, a while loop inside a while loop, or a for loop inside a for loop.

In [5]:
# x = [1, 2]
# y = [4, 5]
 
# for i in x:
#   for j in y:
#     print(i, j)

# CODE OUTPUT
# 1 4
# 1 5
# 2 4
# 2 5
Code Explanation

Two lists are defined: x with elements [1, 2], and y with elements [4, 5].

The outer loop starts iterating over each element in x.

For each iteration of the outer loop, the inner loop starts iterating over each element in y.

Inside the inner loop, the code prints the values of i (current element of x) and j (current element of y).

After printing the values, the inner loop moves to the next element in y.

Once the inner loop finishes iterating over all elements in y, the outer loop moves to the next element in x.

The process continues until the outer loop has iterated over all elements in x.

# Exercise 3: Write a program to count the number of items stored in a list.
# num = [23, 34, ‘hello’, 32, 56]
# Expected output
# Total count of items are: 5

#Solution
num = [23, 34, 'hello', 32, 56]
count = 0
for i in range(len(num)):
    count += 1
print("Total count of items are:",count)

# Approach 2
print("Total count of items are:",len(num))

#Code explanation
# The both approch counts the number of items in a list called num using two different approaches.

# In the first approach:

# Initialize a variable count to 0.
# Iterate through the indices of the num list using the range(len(num)) function.
# For each iteration, increment the count variable by 1.
# After the loop, print the total count of items by displaying the value of count along with a message.

# In the second approach:

# Directly print the total count of items in the num list using the len(num) function.
# This approach avoids the need for a loop and a separate counting variable.

# Exercise 4: Write a program to reverse a list in Python. 
# num = [23, 34, ‘hello’, 32, 56]

# Expected output
# [56, 32, ‘hello’, 34, 23]

#Solution
num = [23, 34, 'hello', 32, 56]
print(num[::-1])

#Code Explanation
# num = [23, 34, 'hello', 32, 56]: This line declares a list called num and initializes it with five elements, including integers (23, 34, 32, 56) and a string ('hello').

# print(num[::-1]): This line prints the elements of the num list in reverse order using slicing notation.

# The [::-1] part specifies a slice that starts from the end of the list and moves backwards with a step size of -1, effectively reversing the order.
# The resulting reversed list is then printed to the console.

[56, 32, 'hello', 34, 23]

# Exercise 4: Swap two tuples in Python
# Given:
# tuple1 = (11, 22)
# tuple2 = (99, 88)

#Solution
tuple1 = (11, 22)
tuple2 = (99, 88)
tuple1, tuple2 = tuple2, tuple1
print(tuple2)
print(tuple1)   

#Code Explanation
# tuple1 = (11, 22): This line declares the first tuple, tuple1, with values 11 and 22.
# tuple2 = (99, 88): This line declares the second tuple, tuple2, with values 99 and 88.
# To swap the tuples, we need to reassign their values. Python provides a concise way to achieve this using tuple unpacking.
# tuple1, tuple2 = tuple2, tuple1: This line swaps the values of tuple1 and tuple2. The right-hand side creates a new tuple (99, 88) and assigns it to tuple1, while the original tuple1 value (11, 22) is assigned to tuple2. This effectively swaps the values between the two tuples.
# After the swap, the values of tuple1 become (99, 88), and the values of tuple2 become (11, 22).

(11, 22)
(99, 88)
